attr.title: My decision to live in Austin was motivated by the conviction that I had a story to tell, and that now was the time to tell it. You see, in college I wrote an unfinished history. It was about the figures I loved who searched for meaning in the 20th century in the context of two world wars and the atomic age, and how the view of the whole earth from space in 1968 gave them hope.
attr.content: My decision to live in Austin was motivated by the conviction that I had a story to tell, and that now was the time to tell it. You see, in college I wrote an unfinished history. It was about the figures I loved who searched for meaning in the 20th century in the context of two world wars and the atomic age, and how the view of the whole earth from space in 1968 gave them hope.

attr.title: It was a story about home, and whether home was something you could find again after you'd lost it.
attr.content: It was a story about home, and whether home was something you could find again after you'd lost it.

attr.title: Because that story was the only thing that felt true to me at the time, I figured I'd live with my brother in Austin and finish it. Finding a job would be easy enough, I reasoned. And I could audit courses at the University of Texas to do that "finding out if grad school is right for me" thing.

attr.title: Things were going nowhere with my whole earth project. I shared what I wrote in college with the folks in my story who were still alive (like Whole Earth Catalog founder Stewart Brand), along with relevant players in the academy.

attr.title: Impressed though they were, they all counseled me to go to grad school to expand the project. My former thesis advisor Ben was a notable exception. "Grad school will rob you of your creativity," he warned.

attr.title: Michael was heading to Apple Computer in Cupertino to become an engineer, and he wanted some company for the journey there. We'd meet up at Reed College in Portland, OR - where we went to school and where his things were in storage - and drive down the west coast in a U-Haul.
attr.content: Michael was heading to Apple Computer in Cupertino to become an engineer, and he wanted some company for the journey there. We'd meet up at Reed College in Portland, OR - where we went to school and where his things were in storage - and drive down the west coast in a U-Haul.

attr.title: I missed the west coast terribly. My first exposure came when I was 16, after my first girlfriend dumped me and I spent all my money on a ticket to Portland, OR to see Bob Dylan in concert and go on a roadtrip through the Pacific Northwest with my mentor David Carter. He told me about Reed College, taught me about the Beat poets, and took me to some of their old stomping grounds.
attr.content: I missed the west coast terribly. My first exposure came when I was 16, after my first girlfriend dumped me and I spent all my money on a ticket to Portland, OR to see Bob Dylan in concert and go on a roadtrip through the Pacific Northwest with my mentor David Carter. He told me about Reed College, taught me about the Beat poets, and took me to some of their old stomping grounds.

attr.title: A visit to Desolation Peak with David Carter, where Beat poets Jack Kerouac and Gary Snyder lived as fire lookouts in the 1950s.
attr.content: A visit to Desolation Peak with David Carter, where Beat poets Jack Kerouac and Gary Snyder lived as fire lookouts in the 1950s.

attr.title: Over the years the region became my natural habitat, and the prospect of roadtripping through it again and spending a few days in the Bay Area made my heart sing.
attr.content: Over the years the region became my natural habitat, and the prospect of roadtripping through it again and spending a few days in the Bay Area made my heart sing.

attr.title: The Zeega platform allows users to combine personal content with media from across the web to create beautiful, immersive online experiences. It was built to catalyze a paradigm shift in the web from being primarily a text-based medium to an audiovisual one.
attr.content: The Zeega platform allows users to combine personal content with media from across the web to create beautiful, immersive online experiences. It was built to catalyze a paradigm shift in the web from being primarily a text-based medium to an audiovisual one.

attr.title: I was part of one of the first few batches of users to receive a Zeega account. I didn't know how to program (I still don't). Never had a website. Never tried crafting one. I did some video editing in high school, but that's about it. The metaLAB assured me that was alright, and that Zeega was built for folks like me to express ourselves creatively on the web.
attr.content: I was part of one of the first few batches of users to receive a Zeega account. I didn't know how to program (I still don't). Never had a website. Never tried crafting one. I did some video editing in high school, but that's about it. The metaLAB assured me that was alright, and that Zeega was built for folks like me to express ourselves creatively on the web.

attr.title: What mattered wasn't my ability to code, but whether I had a story to tell.
attr.content: What mattered wasn't my ability to code, but whether I had a story to tell.

attr.title: And I did, I did.
attr.content: And I did, I did.

attr.title: So I started chugging away on the Zeega platform while carrying on my Bay Area existence, skyping with my brother in Texas (conveniently a web designer) for advice and feedback. My bosses at the coffee shop never had much respect for my time, and would routinely ask that I come in at times when I wasn't scheduled.

attr.title: The early days of Zeega were...challenging. Without much precedence in the form of examples to follow, it was hard to know what was possible. Also, because the platform was in the early alpha phase, bugs abounded. My project would routinely stop working, sometimes disappearing into the void, only to return after a few days of troubleshooting by the Zeega team. Coupled with draft deadlines and an already poor internet connection at my crib in Berkeley, the process led to much weeping and gnashing of teeth.
attr.content: The early days of Zeega were...challenging. Without much precedence in the form of examples to follow, it was hard to know what was possible. Also, because the platform was in the early alpha phase, bugs abounded. My project would routinely stop working, sometimes disappearing into the void, only to return after a few days of troubleshooting by the Zeega team. Coupled with draft deadlines and an already poor internet connection at my crib in Berkeley, the process led to much weeping and gnashing of teeth.

attr.title: But then, things clicked. And slowly a creature started to form. In late March I sent a draft to the metaLAB.
attr.content: But then, things clicked. And slowly a creature started to form. In late March I sent a draft to the metaLAB.

attr.title: The metaLAB loved it! And, they invited me to head to Harvard in June to workshop my project in a room full of metaLAB scholars, journalists, and documentarians.
attr.content: The metaLAB loved it! And, they invited me to head to Harvard in June to workshop my project in a room full of metaLAB scholars, journalists, and documentarians.

attr.title: And so, with my brother in tow, I made my way to Boston.

attr.title: After the workshop, I went to the Zeega studio and discussed my future over a beer with Jesse, one of the Zeega co-founders. I told him I wanted to be a part of this kind of community that had empowered my creative vision.

attr.title: When I returned to the Bay, I applied for and was accepted as a fellow at the metaLAB for the 2012-13 school year.

attr.title: Don't get me wrong, I love San Francisco. It was and always will be where I belong, and I have a feeling it won't be long before I'm back. It's just that, for the first time in a long time, I found direction. I found a path. And that path led to the miserably cold East coast environs of Boston, MA.
